Few Seats Go On Sale

For Series

Tickets for the 1950-1951 Duke University All-Star Concert Se- ries are still available to fresh- ‘men, according to J. Foster Barnes, director.

Only a limited number of tick- ets have been held from general sale for new students. Barnes stated that this year’s series is already a sell-out, and that stu- dents will be unable to purchase tickets after next Tuesday.

Tickets may be purchased on West Campus in the YMCA office Saturday morning. Freshmen women may purchase their tick- ets Monday morning in the East Duke building. i

Traubel Opens

_ The concert series opens with Helen . Traubel, famous Metro- politan Opera Wagnerian § so- prano, on October 16. The next feature will be the Royal Phil- harmonic Orchestra of London, conducted by Sir Thomas Beech- am.

The- series includes, later in the season, Alexander Brailow- sky, pianist; Guiseppe di Stefano, tenor, and the Vienna Choir Boys. .

Two extra attractions, not on the regular concert series, have been scheduled. Lauritz Mel- chior, world-famous heroic ten- or, and the Ballet Theatre will present special programs.

Tickets for these two extra features may be purchased in Room 201 of the West Campus Union, or by writing J. Foster Barnes, Box 4822, Duke Station, Durham.

The concert series has been a popular attraction on the cam- pus among both students and townfolks for several years, bringing outstanding artists to Duke. >

MSGA Entorees Duke’s Traditions

On All Freshmen

West Campus freshmen begin wearing their class hats this week, as Duke traditions are en- forced for the third post-war year.

As during the past two years, each freshman must buy and wear a distinctive hat displaying his class numerals. will be worn at all times on the campus and downtown, except when dating, eating in the din- ing halls, and on Sundays from 7am. to 7 p.m.

Freshman hats must be worn until after the Duke-North Caro- lina football game. If Duke wins the game, the hats may be re- ' moved for good. If not, they will be required until the Christmas holidays.

- Every freshman will be re- quired to learn the songs and cheers used by Duke at football games. Any upperclassman may stop a freshman at any time and ask him to repeat these songs and cheers.

Guard Bonfire

On the eve of the Carolina game, the freshmen will build and guard a bonfire which is burned each year during a pre- game prep rally.

Freshmen are forbidden to use the path known as the Senior Walk, or sit on the Chapel steps. They must tip their hats to any instructor whom they recognize and to upperclassmen who ad- dress them. They are forbidden to add any embellishments or ornaments to their hats.

The Freshman Board of Re- view will enforce the requite- ments of these traditions. The Board has the power to hear cases and punish violators. In extreme cases, the offending freshman may be sent to the dean’s office for official adminis- trative action.

No Hazing

Beta Omega Sigma, honorary sophomore leadership fraternity, and the Freshman Advisory Council are helping SGA to make the program work smooth- ly. Upperclassmen are expected to report any observed violations or hazing or freshmen to mem- bers of BOS or FAC.

The purpose of the traditions program is to impress upon -each freshman the importance of school spirit, and to develop a class loyalty to Duke University. Upperclassmen are not to haze or maltreat fueshmen, and noth- ing is included in the traditions program which the freshman might consider an affront to his dignity or honor. —

WDBS Opens Tonight

With Hour

Broadcast

Duke’ s new radio station WDBS will take the air for the first time this year with an hour broadcast tonight from 10 to 11 p.m. announced station manager Bob Cook. The program will begin a

series of “‘spot’? announcements

to be aired during Orientation

Week for the benefit of incoming freshmen.

WDBS, operating on a fre- quency of 560 kilocycles, is Duke’s newest organization, which began broadcasting a short week before the close of the school year last spring. The entire operation is carried on by a crew of student engineers, and a business and production staff.

Chance for Freshmen

Pointing out that WDBS is a

new organization, Cook added that the station offers unlimited, opportunities for freshmen in- terested in -working on the sep- arate -staffs. A meeting for all those interested in working on any of the staffs will be held at the office, Grey 06, Saturday afternoon, September 16; from 3 until 6 p.m. Freshmen inter- ested in WDBS work «should plan to be interviewed at this time, Cook added. Plans for the current year call for a regular operating schedule to take effect after the formal opening night early in October. WDBS will cover both campuses on a carrier current system. Now operating only on West campus, the station will include East Campus as soon as the booster transmitter to be located on East Campus and now_on order, ar- rives. In conjunction with the Freshman Orientation program, WDBS will feature announce- ments about orientation, general information about Duke Univer- sity, and “live” interviews with freshmen.

Contractors have until 2 p.m. September 20 to submit bids for Duke’s multi-million dollar grad- uate men’s dormitory. A. S. Brower, Duke business manager and comptroller announced this week. Plans for the new build- ing have already been completed and distributed to prospective bidders.

The building is the first project under Duke’s $12,000,000 Devel- opment Program. Designed_ to hold 400 students, the new dor- mitory will also. provide dining and recreation facilities.

Consiruction is expected to be- gin immediately after the con- tracts have been let, and the building should be ready for oc- cupancy by the Fall of 1951.

Frontages of the building will be 311 feet facing Duke Hospital Drive and 193 feet on the Erwin Road side. The building will face the Elizabeth P. Hanes

House, new nurses home now under construction.

The building will be of Geor- gian architecture, in keeping with all the newer buildings here, and will be of brick and limestone. -Architects for the projects ‘are from the office of Horace Thumbauer, Philadel- phia.

Fresh Statisties

Figures released this week by the admissions office showed 636 freshmen boys registered as of September 8. Of this number, 172 are from North Carolina and 145 from other Southeastern states.

From the Mid-Atlantic states are 213 freshmen; 29 come from New England, 52 from the Mid- west, six from the Southwest, seven from the Far West, and 12 from foreign countries. Included in the 686 total are 17 veterans, the lowest number in several

By Nick HENNESSEE Beginning his second year as Dean of Freshman, Dr. William C. Archie yesterday launched a busy week as chief of the orien-

tation program by welcoming}

the some 650 members of the Class of °54 to Trinity College and the College of Engineering.

A tradition at Duke for many years, the work of the freshman office, headed by the affable French professor, is designed to provide within the framework of a large university a personal touch similar to a small college environment.

Dean Archie, a member of the Duke faculty since 1946, ex-

plained the purpose and func-

tion of his office by stressing the important part taken by upper- class and graduate students and the faculty in completing a well- rounded program for the fresh- men, not just during Orientation Week but -also cea eae the year. Free Ravicn

In the office, located at 101 Administration, all the records, both academic and personal, of: the class are kept. Free advice is always available and Dr. Archie urged all the freshmen to take advantage of the office fa- cilities when difficulties arise or are anticipated. “We will help them if we can or we will find someone who can,” he said. “We are here to heckle the student when he lags behind and to pat him on the back when he de- serves it.” ae

“As I have followed the velopment of this class,” added, “it has appeared, on

|per, to be a good one. Football ‘\prospects are looking up with

about 40 having been invited down several weeks ago for early practice. Evidence is that

they are working hard, and one

thing is certain, they are really a husky crew.”

Housemasters

Primarily, the work of the freshman office is channeled through the six graduate house- masters and twelve undergrad- uate assistants in the seven freshman dormitories located in Kilgo quadrangle, the dean ex- plained. They serve as coun- selors within the dormitories and are in charge of the houses. Heading the housemaster staff is Dr. A. H. Strobel of the Chem- istry department.

The assistant housemasters were picked from the Freshman Advisory Council. Approximate- ly 100 other members of the council, headed by Jim Briggs, will work with them toward im- proving the lot of the freshmen and working them into the oe routine.

Trouble Shooters

* Trouble-shooting specialists in academic work are the members of Phi Eta Sigma, sophomore so- ciety honoring the top scholars in the Class of ’53. Also avail- able are the services of faculty advisers who work with the of- fice.

In the service vane, membéis of Beta Omega Sigma will pro- mote freshman activity and school spirit through sponsor- ship of pep rallies and the first fall formal.

Before coming to the Univer- sity faculty, Dr. Archie ‘taught at Wake Forest College. He holds an A.B. degree from Davidson (1929), and M.A. from Wake Forest (1935), and M:A. and Ph.D. degrees from Princeton. Now, in addition to his freshman duties, he is assistant professor in the Romance Language de- partment.

An interpreter for General Dwight Eisenhower at the first Allies Control Council meeting in Berlin, July 30, 1945, he served during World War II as Counter Intelligence Officer, Public Relations Officer, and as assistant U. S. Secretary of Mili- tary Government for the United States in Berlin.

Duke’s Glee Clubs Gifts,

Hold Auditions September 12 to 16

Freshman and transfer stu- dents will have an opportunity this week to try out for both the Men’s and Women’s Glee Clubs of the University.

The Men’s Glee Club, under the direction of J. Foster Barnes, has gained national recognition during a series of tours through- out the eastern states and four- teen performances over a na- tional radio network.

Exceptional members of the Women’s Glee Club are selected for the Chapel Choir or the Tri- ple Trio. The Women’s Glee Club, directed by Mrs. Barnes, is primarily a training unit for these musical groups. _

Chapel Choir

The Chapel Choir is composed of selected members of both glee clubs.

Men’s tryouts will be held in

the basement of the Chapel next

Monday and Tuesday afternoons from 3 to 5 p.m. There will be a special tryout session for upper- classman transfer students Tues- day evening, from 7 to 9 p.m.

Mrs. Barnes will hold audi- tions for freshman and transfer students Tuesday and Wednes- day, from 3 to 5 p.m. in the Mu- sic Room at 201 East Duke build- ing.

A special choir practice will be held next Friday night for all returning members of the Chapel Choir.

Perkins Asks New

Vets to Contact Office for Checks

Freshmen veterans should con- tact Barbara Perkins immedi- ately in the Veterans Adminis- tration office, 302 Administration Building, to get their veterans records so that payment of sub- sistence checks will be prompt.

Fewer than 20 veterans have enrolled in this year’s freshman class, stated Miss Perkins. The number of veterans in this year’s

class is about equal to the enroll-

ment last year.

The enrollment of veterans at Duke shows a marked decrease from last year when 1700 vet- erans attended compared with only 900 here this fall.

That Box Number!

All mail not carrying box num- bers will be returned to the sender, J. C. Allen, superintend- ent of the Duke Station Post Of- fice, announced today in urging all boxholders immediately to notify their families and friends of their new addresses.

This also applies to College Station, Hospital Station, and other offices, he stated, since new postal regulations do not permit the use of directory service for boxing mail. _
